   <h1 align="center"> 
Attorney General Ellison stops physician from deceptively soliciting donations  </h1>
   
<p class="lede">Agreement bans Excelsior-based wellness physician Sean OâMara from soliciting for a nonexistent charity, falsely claiming charitability and tax-deductibility, and engaging in other deceptive tactics</p>
<p class="lede">Refers findings to Board of Medical Practice</p>




  
 
     <p><strong>June 14, 2023 (SAINT PAUL)Â </strong>â Minnesota Attorney General Keith Ellison today announced that he has filed anÂ <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2023/docs/OMara_AoD.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" data-auth="NotApplicable" data-linkindex="0">Assurance of Discontinuance</a>Â that prohibits an Excelsior-based wellness physician Sean O&rsquo;Mara, and his practice Medical Concierge Wellness, P.L.L.C. (&ldquo;MedCon Wellness&rdquo;), from soliciting contributions for a charity that did not exist, falsely claiming on his web site that fees paid to his clinic benefited charity and were tax-deductible, and other misleading statements on his web site.Â </p>
     
     <p>&ldquo;The doctorâpatient relationship should be one of complete trust,&rdquo; Attorney General Ellison stated. &ldquo;Dr. O&rsquo;Mara abused the trust of prospective patients and donors by claiming that clinic fees and donations would benefit a nonexistent charity. This Assurance prohibits him from making these claims in the future. I have also forwarded my findings to the Minnesota Board of Medical Practice, who is in the best position to assess whether this conduct raises medical ethics concerns or other violations.&rdquo;Â </p>
     
     <p>In the Assurance of Discontinuance filed today, the Attorney General specifically alleged that Dr.Â O&rsquo;Mara violated charities laws by falsely telling prospective patients that they would &ldquo;be eligible for a deduction from [their] taxes by working with Dr. Sean&rsquo;s Nonprofit or pay for your consultation with pretax dollars as a business expense.&rdquo; The Attorney General alleged that in reality, Dr. O&rsquo;Mara &ldquo;never created any nonprofit&rdquo; and &ldquo;provided consultations through MedCon Wellness, which is not tax-exempt&rdquo; or eligible for tax deductions. Â </p>
     
     <p>The Attorney General also alleged in the Assurance that Dr. O&rsquo;Mara &ldquo;solicited contributions through his website, requesting funds via a PayPal link, phone calls, and the private messaging app WhatsApp&rdquo; for a nonexistent charity. Dr. O&rsquo;Mara also promised to &ldquo;donate all [his] professional fees&rdquo; to charity if a customer was not satisfied, but never made any such donations. The Assurance further notes that Dr. O&rsquo;Mara has a past medical licensing history that involve allegations of misleading conduct. The Assurance holds Dr. O&rsquo;Mara accountable for $25,000 for each occurrence if he violates the Assurance in the future.Â </p>
     
    <p>In Minnesota, the Attorney General through the Charities Division has civil enforcement authority over the solicitation of charitable contributions. UnderÂ <a href="https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/309.50" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" data-auth="NotApplicable" data-linkindex="1">state</a>Â <a href="https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/309.55" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" data-auth="NotApplicable" data-linkindex="2">law</a>, no person purporting to engage in solicitation for a charitable purpose may use or employ any false promise, misrepresentation, or misleading statement in connection with a charitable solicitation. The Attorney General&rsquo;s Office provides additional information and resources about charitable solicitation laws on itsÂ <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Charity/Default.asp" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" data-auth="NotApplicable" data-linkindex="3">Charities homepage</a>.Â The Charities Division does not enforce criminal laws.Â </p>
     
     <p>The public may submit complaints to the Attorney General about potential misconduct or other concerns, eitherÂ <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Charity/FileAComplaint.asp" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" data-auth="NotApplicable" data-linkindex="4">online</a>Â or by calling (651) 296-3353 (Metro area), (800) 657-3787 (Greater Minnesota), or (800) 627-3529 (Minnesota Relay).Â Â  </p>
